Got it You're essentially asking for a well-crafted master prompt that you could feed into an AI website builder (or design tool like Figma, Framer, Webflow, or even ChatGPTbased code generation) to produce a professional, full-featured website for a transformer manufacturing company.

Below is a detailed prompt you can use/adapt that covers all the features and structure a typical manufacturing company website should have.

Master Prompt for AI Website Generation

(For a Transformer Manufacturing Company)

Prompt:

You are a professional web designer and developer tasked with creating a complete, modern, and responsive corporate website for a Transformer Manufacturing Company. The website should provide a strong industrial brand presence, showcase products and services clearly, and include all the necessary corporate/manufacturing-specific sections. The design should be modern, professional, and user-friendly, with clean layouts, strong CTAs (Call-to-Actions), and trust-building elements.

Design & Style

  • Professional corporate look with an industrial/engineering feel.

  • Theme colors: Blue, Grey, and White (symbolizing trust, technology, precision).

  • Typography: Modern sans-serif (e.g., Open Sans, Roboto, Inter).

  • Responsive design (desktop, tablet, mobile).

  • Sticky header with company logo, navigation, and quick CTA button ("Request a Quote").

Website Pages & Features

1. Homepage

  • Hero section: High-quality banner image of transformers, headline about power & reliability, and CTA button ("Explore Products" / "Request a Quote").

  • Overview: Brief about the companys history, scale, and expertise.

  • Key product categories with images, short descriptions, and links to detail pages.

  • "Why Choose Us" trusted by industries, certifications (ISO, CE, etc.), years of experience, global presence, after-sales support.

  • Partner logos or client industries served (e.g., Power Distribution, Industrial Plants, Renewable Energy).

  • Quick inquiry form at the bottom.

2. About Us

  • Company introduction (history, mission, vision, values).

  • Leadership team / CEO message.

  • Manufacturing facilities (factory images, R&D capabilities, technology used).

  • Certifications & compliance (ISO, IEEE, Environmental Standards).

3. Products & Specifications

(Each product page should show technical details in a structured table)

  • Product Categories (e.g.):

    • Distribution Transformers

    • Power Transformers

    • Dry-Type Transformers

    • Oil-Cooled Transformers

    • Special Purpose/Custom Transformers

  • Each product page should include:

    • Product image(s) / CAD drawings

    • Description of applications

    • Technical specifications (Capacity, Voltage Class, Cooling Type, Standards compliance) in downloadable PDF datasheets

    • Key benefits & features

    • Request a quote button

4. Industries Served

  • Showcase sectors that use these products: Utilities, Renewable Energy, Manufacturing Plants, Commercial Infrastructure, Defense, etc.

  • Add case studies or success stories (optional).

5. Services

  • After-sales support

  • Installation & commissioning

  • Maintenance contracts

  • Repairs, testing, and calibration services

  • Spare parts availability

6. Quality & Compliance

  • Testing facilities (high voltage test labs, type tests, routine tests).

  • Details about international certifications and QA processes.

  • Safety and sustainability standards.

7. Downloads / Resources

  • Product catalogs (PDF)

  • Technical brochures

  • Certificates (ISO, BIS, IEC, CE, etc.)

  • User manuals

8. Careers

  • Current job openings

  • Internship opportunities

  • Culture, employee benefits

  • Job application upload form

9. Contact Us

  • Contact form (Name, Email, Phone, Message, File upload for RFQs).

  • Office addresses, factory location with map integration.

  • Phone numbers, emails of sales & support.

  • Distributor/Dealer network (if applicable).

10. Blog / News (Optional)

  • Industry updates, company news, technology trends.

11. Footer (Global)

  • Quick links (About, Products, Services, Careers, Contact).

  • Certifications/Badges (ISO, CE, etc.).

  • Social media links (LinkedIn, YouTube, Twitter).

  • Copyright text.

Technical Requirements

  • Stack: Modern web framework (React.js, Next.js, or WordPress if CMS needed).

  • Optimized for SEO with structured metadata (title, description, OpenGraph).

  • Fast load time, image optimization.

  • Multi-language support (English + optional German/Spanish for international market).

  • Admin interface for uploading new product datasheets, blogs, certifications.

  • Secure forms with spam protection (Google reCAPTCHA).

Extra Suggestions

  • Add 360 product view/gallery for some transformers.

  • Integration with CRM/email marketing tools (HubSpot, Zoho, Mailchimp).

  • "Request a Quote" button always visible in nav.

  • Option to compare specifications of different transformers.

This prompt covers: corporate presentation + product details + customer engagement + trust elements everything a real manufacturing companys site would typically need.

Clean HTML/CSS hero example

  • Pattern: full-bleed hero with gradient overlay for legibility.w3schools

xml
<section class="hero">
  <div class="hero__content">
    <h1>Powering Reliable Distribution</h1>
    <p>Engineered transformers for utilities, industry, and renewables.</p>
    <div class="hero__actions">
      <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/products">Explore Products</a>
      <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/contact">Request a Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

css
.hero {
  min-height: 80vh;
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
  text-align: center;
  color: #fff;
  background:
    linear-gradient(rgba(0,0,0,.55), rgba(0,0,0,.55)),
    url("/assets/transformer-substation-170380327.jpg") center/cover no-repeat;
}
.hero__content { padding: 0 1.5rem; max-width: 72ch; }
.hero__actions { display: inline-flex; gap: 12px; margin-top: 16px; }
.btn { padding: 12px 20px; border-radius: 8px; font-weight: 600; }
.btn--primary { background:#1f5fbf; color:#fff; }
.btn--ghost { border:1px solid #fff; color:#fff; background:transparent; }
@media (max-width: 600px) { .hero { min-height: 60vh; } .hero__actions { flex-direction: column; width: 100%; } }

This follows standard hero best practices: cover background, gradient overlay, and responsive layout for readability.w3schools+1

.bookmark-card:hover { transform: translateY(-4px); box-shadow: 0 10px 24px rgba(0,0,0,.14); }
.bookmark-card__media img { width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; border-radius:10px; }
.bookmark-card__cta { color:#1f5fbf; font-weight:600; }
@media (max-width:600px){ .bookmark-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

This gives the bookmark feel while keeping UX and accessibility intact.shopify+1

Heres a single copy-paste master prompt you can use in a design/code generator. It references the screenshots and fixes the overflow, adds consistent hover panels for all tabs except Home, and makes every Know more / Learn more action functional.

Prompt:

Update the TransPower website header, hover panels, and card actions using the attached screenshots as visual reference. Maintain the same visual language (spacing, corners, shadows, typography) and the exact hero and card styling already present.

Navigation and hover behavior

  • Tabs in order: Home, About Us, Products, Industries, Quality, Request a Quote.

  • Do NOT add any dropdown chevrons or icons next to tab labels.

  • Apply hover/focus panels to all tabs except Home and Request a Quote. Home has no panel; Request a Quote remains a primary button without a panel.

  • Each panel opens when hovering over the tab or focusing it via keyboard (delay 140ms), and closes on pointer leave/focus out (delay 120ms) or Escape.

  • Include a Know more action inside each panel that navigates to the corresponding top-level page. Keep panel copy minimal (1-line description max or no description) to match the Products pattern; do not add long summaries.

Overflow and positioning fix (addresses panel going off-screen)

  • Constrain the hover panel to the viewport and the header container:

    • Position strategy: Use a smart anchored popover that calculates available space and flips/ shifts as needed.

    • Horizontal behavior: If panel width would overflow the right edge, shift it left so right edge aligns to viewport (max-inline-size: min(720px, calc(100vw - 24px))). If it would overflow left, shift right similarly.

    • Vertical behavior: Default to open below the tab; if not enough space below, open above the header with the same elevation and arrowless style.

    • Use transform-origin to match final placement (top center when below, bottom center when above) and animate scale 0.98 1 with opacity 0 1 over 160ms.

    • Add 8px pointer-leave tolerance between tab and panel to prevent accidental closes.

    • Panel container styles: border-radius 12px; shadow comparable to 1216dp; background surface same as Products panel; padding 24px; z-index above hero.

    • Prevent layout shifts: panel is position: fixed (preferred) or absolutely positioned within a fixed header layer; never push content.

Accessibility

  • Tabs are buttons/links with aria-haspopup="menu", aria-expanded, and aria-controls for their panels.

  • Panel role="menu" with menuitems as links; implement roving tabindex for Arrow key navigation; Tab/Shift+Tab traverse items; Enter/Space activates; Escape closes and returns focus to the triggering tab.

  • Focus ring visible (23px or offset outline). Hit area min 4040 px.

Tab-specific panels (minimal content + Know more)

  • About Us panel: simple list of 3 links (Company, Leadership, Facilities) plus Know more that routes to /about.

  • Products panel: keep current two-column list exactly as in the screenshot with the View All Products footer. Ensure the panel respects the overflow rules above.

  • Industries panel: 46 industry links (Utilities, Renewables, Manufacturing, Commercial, Defense). Include Know more to /industries.

  • Quality panel: 34 links (Certifications, Testing, Compliance, Sustainability) and Know more to /quality.

Make all Know more / Learn more actions functional

  • In every panel, Know more must be a working link to the tabs landing page.

  • In the Services section cards on the homepage, the Learn more links must scroll to the in-page /services anchor or open the corresponding service detail (modal or dedicated section). Do not leave them as placeholders.

  • Ensure pointer cursor, proper hrefs, and focusable states for all Know more / Learn more elements.

Responsive and mobile behavior

  • On touch devices, tapping a tab (except Home/Request a Quote) toggles the panel open; tapping outside or pressing Back closes it.

  • Panels become full-width sheets anchored under the header, with the same content and a prominent Know more at the bottom. No chevrons on tab labels.

  • Prevent body scroll when a mobile panel is open; return scroll position on close.

Performance and polish

  • Prefetch tab target routes on hover/focus for faster navigation.

  • Use GPU-accelerated transforms for animation; prefer fixed positioning to avoid layout thrash.

  • Respect the current color scheme and typography; match the Products panel visual exactly across panels for consistency.

Acceptance criteria

  • Panels never overflow the viewport; they shift/flip to remain fully visible.

  • All tabs except Home and Request a Quote show accessible hover/focus panels without adding dropdown icons next to labels.

  • Every Know more / Learn more link navigates to a real route or in-page anchor and is keyboard-accessible.

  • Services cards Learn more are fully functional.

  • Visual style matches the existing Products panel and the screenshots.

Heres a single, copypaste master prompt that documents the current bugs, specifies desired behavior, and instructs the AI to implement robust hover panels, correct spacing, accurate positioning after scroll, and working clicks/links for tabs and Services cards.

Prompt:

Context

  • Site: TransPower manufacturing website with sticky top navigation and hover panels for tabs.

  • Reference: The current header shows tabs Home About Us Products Industries Quality plus a Request a Quote button on the right (see attached screenshot).

  • Current issues to fix are listed below. Implement fixes without changing visual style, typography, or colors already in use.

Bugs to fix (describe and address)

  1. Header tab spacing inconsistent

  • Problem: The inline tabs are cramped/uneven (insufficient gap between Home About Us Products Industries Quality).

  • Fix: Apply consistent horizontal spacing using a flex container with gap tokens (desktop: 2832px; tablet: 2024px; mobile: 1620px). Ensure tabs do not wrap; when space is tight, collapse gaps responsively or switch to a mobile menu. Maintain vertical alignment with the Request a Quote button.

  1. Hover panel mispositioned after scroll

  • Problem: When the page is scrolled down and a tab is hovered, the info panel renders offscreen above the viewport, as if position calculations ignored scroll offset.

  • Fix: Use viewportrelative positioning and correct anchor math:

    • Prefer position: fixed for the popover panel, anchored to the tabs boundingClientRect relative to the viewport, not the document.

    • Compute x/y as:
      const rect = trigger.getBoundingClientRect();
      const top = rect.bottom + OFFSET; // no need to add window.scrollY when using fixed
      const left = clamp(rect.left + rect.width/2 - panelWidth/2, 12, viewportWidth - panelWidth - 12);

    • If using position: absolute within a fixed/sticky header layer, include window.scrollY in y calculation.

    • Implement flip/shift middleware: if not enough room below, open above; if panel would overflow right/left, shift within viewport.

  1. Hover works, but clicking a tab doesnt navigate

  • Problem: Tab click is being intercepted by hover/open handlers (e.preventDefault) or the tab is a button without an href.

  • Fix: Make each tab a semantic link (<a href="/route">) for navigation, wrapped in a focusable trigger element only if necessary. Do not prevent default on click; on click, close any open panel and navigate to the href. On keyboard Enter/Space, follow the link. Maintain aria-expanded updates only for hover/focus states, not blocking navigation.

  1. Services cards Learn more not opening any page

  • Problem: The cards show Learn more but the action has no target or is a span.

  • Fix: Convert to actual links (<a>) with valid hrefs (either inpage anchors like /#services/[slug], modal routes, or dedicated pages /services/[slug]). Ensure target routes exist and are prefetchable; add role="link", tabindex=0 if necessary; provide pointer and focus states.

Required behavior and specifications

Header layout and spacing

  • Container: display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between.

  • Tabs container: display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 32px (desktop), 24px (tablet), 18px (mobile). No extra nonbreaking spaces. Use padding-inline: 812px per tab for touch targets.

  • Minimum hit area for tabs: 4040 px with visible focus ring.

Hover/focus panels (all tabs except Home and Request a Quote)

  • Trigger: hover or keyboard focus on tab.

  • Open delay: 140180ms; close delay: 120160ms to prevent flicker.

  • Positioning: position: fixed; compute from getBoundingClientRect; never rely on document scroll offsets for fixed panels.

  • Collision handling:

    • Horizontal: clamp within viewport with 12px margins; flip/shift middleware.

    • Vertical: default open below; if insufficient space below, open above (transform-origin toggles accordingly).

  • Panel styling: 12px radius; elevation shadow (1216dp equivalent); padding 24px; z-index above header; pointerleave tolerance area of 8px to prevent jitter.

  • Accessibility:

    • Each tab link has aria-haspopup="menu", aria-expanded (true/false), and aria-controls set when the panel is visible.

    • Panel role="menu"; items role="menuitem" and are <a> links.

    • Roving tabindex for arrowkey navigation; Tab/Shift+Tab traverse links; Escape closes panel and returns focus to the tab.

    • Close on outside click or Escape; trap focus while open.

  • Interaction contract:

    • Hover shows panel; moving from tab to panel keeps it open (hoverintent tolerance).

    • Clicking the tab navigates to its href immediately (do not prevent default).

    • Clicking Know more in a panel navigates to the tabs landing route.

    • Clicking a product/category link navigates to that route.

Panels content (keep minimal; consistent with Products)

  • About Us: list of 3 quick links; bottom Know more to /about.

  • Products: existing twocolumn category list; bottom View All Products to /products.

  • Industries: 46 quick links; bottom Know more to /industries.

  • Quality: 34 quick links; bottom Know more to /quality.

  • Do NOT add chevrons next to tab labels.

Services cards actions

  • Convert every Learn more into a functioning link:

    • href patterns: /services/installation-commissioning, /services/preventive-maintenance, /services/repairs-overhauls, /services/testing-calibration, /services/retrofit-upgrades, /services/spares-consumables.

    • Option A: route to dedicated pages; Option B: open modal with detailed content and a Go to service page link; Option C: scroll to inpage anchors with unique IDs (#installation, #maintenance, etc.).

  • Ensure these links are focusable, have visible focus states, and are tracked for analytics if available.

Event handling details (pseudocode)

  • Tabs are links:
    <a class="nav-tab" href="/products" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="panel-products">Products</a>

  • Open on pointerenter/focusin:
    onEnter = () => openPanel('products')

  • Close on pointerleave/focusout with small delay; cancel close if entering panel.

  • Do not call preventDefault in click handler. On click: close panels and allow default navigation.

  • Positioning:
    const rect = trigger.getBoundingClientRect();
    const vw = window.innerWidth, vh = window.innerHeight;
    const panelW = Math.min(720, vw - 24);
    let left = rect.left + rect.width/2 - panelW/2;
    left = Math.max(12, Math.min(left, vw - panelW - 12));
    const spaceBelow = vh - rect.bottom;
    const openAbove = spaceBelow < PANEL_HEIGHT + 16;
    const top = openAbove ? Math.max(12, rect.top - PANEL_HEIGHT - 8) : rect.bottom + 8;
    panel.style.position = 'fixed';
    panel.style.left = ${left}px;
    panel.style.top = ${top}px;

  • Animation: transform-origin: openAbove ? 'bottom center' : 'top center'; use opacity and transform scale for 160ms.

Routing and links

  • Ensure every nav tab has a valid href:
    / -> Home
    /about -> About Us
    /products -> Products
    /industries-> Industries
    /quality -> Quality

  • Ensure every Know more / View All Products / Learn more is a real link with href; add target routes/pages or anchors. Remove placeholder spans.

Testing scenarios to validate

  • Desktop, tablet, mobile.

Hero Image Optimization Techniques

To reduce the size of your hero image visually and optimize its loading/performance, update your component and image setup as follows:

1. CSS Container Height

  • Lower the min-height and max-height or use a percentage-based height for responsiveness. For example:

    jsx
    <div className="relative bg-slate-800 text-white min-h-[300px] lg:h-[60vh] max-h-[500px] flex items-center justify-center text-center">

    • This sets a smaller default and limits max size on large screens.

2. Use the Next.js <Image> Component for Optimization (Recommended)

If you are using Next.js, switch to the <Image> component for built-in resizing and optimization:dhiwise+1

jsx
import Image from 'next/image';
import seedImages from './seedImages';

const HeroSection = () => (
  <div className="relative bg-slate-800 text-white min-h-[300px] lg:h-[60vh] max-h-[500px] flex items-center justify-center text-center">
    <div className="absolute inset-0 overflow-hidden">
      <Image
        src={seedImages.hero}
        alt="High-voltage electrical substation at dusk"
        layout="fill" // fills container size
        objectFit="cover" // cover style
        priority // high-priority loading
        quality={75} // reduces file size
        sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 50vw" // loads smaller for mobile
        placeholder="blur" // blur-up placeholder
        blurDataURL="data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB3aWR0aD0iMTIwMCIgaGVpZ2h0PSI3MjAiIHhtbG5zPSJodHRwOi8vd3d3LnczLm9yZy8yMDAwL3N2ZyI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEyMDAiIGhlaWdodD0iNzIwIiBmaWxsPSIjM2M0NjU3Ii8+PC9zdmc+" // (use your own or Next.js default)
      />
      <div className="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-r from-slate-900/80 via-slate-900/50 to-slate-900/30"></div>
    </div>
    {/* ...hero content... */}
  </div>
);

Key optimization tips:

  • Lower the value for min-h and max-h in the container.

  • Compress the hero image in advance (e.g., using TinyPNG or WebP conversion).refine+1

  • Use responsive sizes so mobile devices dont download giant images.

  • Use the blur placeholder for better perceived load speed.nextjs+1

  • If you cannot use Next.jss <Image>, manually lower the CSS height and compress the image.

Summary: Adjust your containers height, use Next.js <Image> with responsive and compressed images, and youll drastically reduce the hero image size and improve the sites speed and usability. Existing page elements will not be affected.

which line can be used to modify the height and width of the card  // Top card         {             initial: { opacity: 0, y: 40, rotate: 12, scale: 1 },             animate: {                 opacity: 1,                 y: isHovered ? -20 : 0,                 rotate: isHovered ? 18 : 6,                 x: isHovered ? 50 : 0,                 scale: 1,             },             transition: { type: 'spring' as const, stiffness: 300, damping: 20 },             className: "z-30"         },

To modify the height and width of the card in this Framer Motion variant object, you can directly animate these properties by adding them to the initial and animate states (Framer Motion supports animating CSS properties like height and width). This allows for smooth transitions without needing extra CSS, though you could also control them via the className or external styles if preferred.

Updated Code Snippet

Here's the modified object with height and width added (I've set example valuesadjust them as needed, e.g., to pixels, percentages, or variables). I've made them responsive to the hover state for a dynamic effect, but you can keep them static if desired.

javascript
// Top card
{
    initial: { 
        opacity: 0, 
        y: 40, 
        rotate: 12, 
        scale: 1,
        height: '150px',  // Initial height (e.g., smaller on load)
        width: '250px'    // Initial width
    },
    animate: {
        opacity: 1,
        y: isHovered ? -20 : 0,
        rotate: isHovered ? 18 : 6,
        x: isHovered ? 50 : 0,
        scale: 1,
        height: isHovered ? '200px' : '180px',  // Expands height on hover
        width: isHovered ? '300px' : '280px'    // Expands width on hover
    },
    transition: { type: 'spring' as const, stiffness: 300, damping: 20 },
    className: "z-30"
},

Key Notes

  • Why these lines? The height and width properties are added directly to initial (starting state) and animate (target state). Framer Motion will interpolate between them during the animation.

  • Customization: Use values like 'auto', percentages (e.g., '50%'), or variables. For conditional sizing (as shown), tie them to states like isHovered.

  • Performance tip: If the card contains content, ensure it reflows properly (e.g., use overflow: hidden in CSS to avoid clipping).

  • Testing: Wrap this in a <motion.div> component in your JSX, and verify it doesn't cause layout shifts (add layout prop if needed for smoother reflows).

If this is part of a larger component or you're using a different animation library, share more code for precise tweaks!
